<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1599" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1599">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.62/100.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">German Chargé
                                        d’Affaires</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Imperial German Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Newport</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-08">
                                        <hi rend="italic">August 8, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: A telegraphic
                                report from the Imperial Consulate at Guadalajara, which did not
                                reach Berlin until the end of July, says that when the
                                Constitutionalist forces took that city on the 8th of last month
                                they respected the interests of German residents.</p>
                            <p>I am instructed to express to the Government of the United States the
                                Imperial Government’s thanks for the friendly readiness with which
                                the threatened German interests were again looked after in this case
                                in a specially effective manner.</p>
                            <p>In having the honor thus to comply with the aforesaid instructions, I
                                have reference to your excellency’s obliging note verbale of June
                                20th last on the subject.<note n="153" xml:id="d1599fn153">Communicated to the German Ambassador, June 20, 1914.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Haniel</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>